\n| rr         = Miraetonghapdang\n| mr         = Miraet'onghaptang\n}}\n\nThe '''United Future Party''' ({{Korean|hangul=\ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9|hanja={{lang|ko-Hant|\u672a\u4f86\u7d71\u5408\u9ee8}} |rr=Miraetonghapdang|lit=''Future Unionist Party''}}) is a [[Conservatism in South Korea|conservative]]<ref>{{cite news |last= Shim |first= Elizabeth |date= 28 February 2020 |title= South Korea president voices concern about Chinese reprisal |url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/02/28/South-Korea-president-voices-concern-about-Chinese-reprisal/2551582906837/ |work= United Press International (UPI) |access-date= 16 March 2020 |quote= Hwang Kyo-ahn, leader of the conservative United Future Party, the main opposition, told Moon it might not be too late to implement a ban to prevent a further increase in cases of COVID-19.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Sang-Hun |first= Choe |date= 19 February 2020 |title= Ex-North Korean Diplomat Runs for South Korean Parliament |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/19/world/asia/north-korean-defector-parliament.html |work= The New York Times |access-date= 16 March 2020 |quote= South Korea\u2019s main conservative political opposition, the United Future Party, selected him to run in National Assembly elections in April.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Si-young |first= Choi |date= 2 March 2020 |title= Public divided over expanding China entry ban |url= http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200302000742 |work= The Korea Herald |access-date= 16 March 2020 |quote= Almost 9 out of 10 supporters of the conservative main opposition United Future Party favored a wider ban that covers all of China.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Ju-min |first= Park |date= 2 March 2020 |title= Wristwatch overshadows South Korea sect leader's coronavirus apology |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southkorea-watch-idUSKBN20P1UM |work= Reuters |access-date= 16 March 2020 |quote= United Future Party, a conservative political movement formerly headed by Park, denied Lee and the party had any political connections.}}</ref> [[list of political parties in South Korea|political party]] in [[South Korea]].\n\nThe party was formed on 17 February 2020 by the merger of the [[Liberty Korea Party]], [[New Conservative Party (South Korea)|New Conservative Party]] and [[Onward for Future 4.0]], as well as several minor parties and political organisations.<ref name=\"future\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 18 February 2020|title= '\uc758\uc11d 113\uc11d' \ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \ucd9c\ubc94\u2026\uc624\ub298 \uc758\uc6d0\ucd1d\ud68c\uc11c \uc0c1\uacac\ub840|url= http://news.tvchosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/18/2020021890024.html|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> By the time of establishment, it contains 118 MPs in the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]].<ref name=\"future\"/> It has a sister relationship with the minor [[Future Korea Party]].\n\n== History ==\n=== Background ===\nThe [[2016 South Korean political scandal|political scandal in 2016]] led [[President of South Korea|President]] [[Park Geun-hye]] to be impeached, and several MPs quit from the then-ruling [[Saenuri Party]] to form the [[Bareun Party]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 24 January 2017|title= \ubc14\ub978\uc815\ub2f9, \ubb34\ub98e \uafc7\uace0 \uc0ac\uc8c4\ud558\uba70 \ucc3d\ub2f9\ub300\ud68c|url= https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/01/24/2017012401575.html|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> The Saenuri Party changed its name to the [[Liberty Korea Party]] (LKP),<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 13 February 2017|title= \uc0c8\ub204\ub9ac\ub2f9, \uc624\ub298 \uc790\uc720\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9\uc73c\ub85c \uac1c\uba85\u2026\uc0c1\uc9d5\uc740 '\ud683\ubd88'|url= https://news.sbs.co.kr/news/endPage.do?news_id=N1004039343|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> but following the [[Impeachment of Park Geun-hye|final impeachment of Park on 10 March 2017]], it ''de jure'' lost its ruling party position.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 10 March 2017|title= [\uc804\ubb38] \uc790\uc720\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9 \"\ud5cc\ubc95\uc7ac\ud310\uc18c \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \ud0c4\ud575 \uc778\uc6a9 \uacb0\uc815 \uacb8\ud5c8\ud558\uac8c \uc218\uc6a9\"|url= https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/2017031092337|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> After the [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]] presidential candidate [[Moon Jae-in]] was [[2017 South Korean presidential election|elected on 9 May]],<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 10 May 2017|title= \ubb38\uc7ac\uc778, \ub4dd\ud45c\uc728 41.08% \u2026\uc5ed\ub300 \ucd5c\ub2e4 \ud45c\ucc28 \ub2f9\uc120|url= https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/05/10/2017051000430.html|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> it officially became the main opposition.\n\nThough several Bareun MPs returned to the LKP, the LKP did not recover its support, losing ground in the [[2018 South Korean local elections|2018 local elections]].<ref name=\"defeat\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 14 June 2018|title= \uc9c0\ubc29\uc120\uac70 \ud328\ubc30, \uc790\uc720\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9 \ud64d\uc900\ud45c \ub300\ud45c\uc9c1 \uc0ac\ud1f4|url= https://www.nocutnews.co.kr/news/4985408|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> Its President, [[Hong Jun-pyo]], immediately resigned in order to take responsibility for the serious defeat.<ref name=\"defeat\"/> The Bareun Party, which had merged with the minor [[centrism|centrist]] [[People's Party (South Korea, 2016)|People's Party]] to form the [[Bareunmirae Party]], also faced a defeat at the local elections.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 14 June 2018|title= [\uc9c0\ubc29\uc120\uac70 \uacb0\uacfc\u2462] \u2018\ubc14\ub978\ubbf8\ub798\ub2f9\u2019 \u00b7\u00b7 \uc65c \ub9dd\ud588\ub098|url= http://www.ejanews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=202909|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoth conservative parties then held snap leadership elections. [[2018 Bareunmirae Party leadership election|On 2 September 2018]], the Bareunmirae Party elected [[Sohn Hak-kyu]] as its new President.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 2 September 2018|title= \ub3cc\uc544\uc628 \uc190\ud559\uaddc... \ubc14\ub978\ube44\ub798 \ub2f9\ub300\ud45c \ub2f9\uc120, 27% \ub4dd\ud45c|url= https://news.joins.com/article/22934682|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> [[2019 Liberty Korea Party leadership election|On 27 February 2019]], the Liberty Korea Party elected former [[Prime Minister of South Korea|Prime Minister]] [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]] as its new President.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 27 February 2019|title= \ud669\uad50\uc548, \ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9 \ub2f9\ub300\ud45c \ub2f9\uc120\u2026\u2018\ud0c4\ud575 \uadf8\ub298\u2019 \uac77\uc5b4\ub0bc\uae4c|url= http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/politics/assembly/883912.html|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> Soon, [[Lee Un-ju]], a Bareunmirae MP, quit her party<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 23 April 2019|title= \uc774\uc5b8\uc8fc \ud0c8\ub2f9\u2026\ubc14\ub978\ubbf8\ub798\ub2f9 \uae68\uc9c0\ub098|url= https://www.mk.co.kr/news/politics/view/2019/04/253581/|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> and was widely expected to join the LKP<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 13 November 2019|title= \uc2e0\ub2f9 \ucc3d\ub2f9 \uc120\uc5b8\ud55c \uc774\uc5b8\uc8fc\u2026\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9\uacfc\ub294 \uacb0\ubcc4?|url= https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/201911133475H|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> but formed a new party named [[Onward for Future 4.0]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 19 January 2020|title= \uc774\uc5b8\uc8fc \uc758\uc6d0 `\ubbf8\ub798\ub97c \ud5a5\ud55c \uc804\uc9c44.0` \uacf5\uc2dd \ucc3d\ub2f9|url= https://www.mk.co.kr/news/politics/view/2020/01/61197/|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> Other former Bareun MPs faced conflicts with its President Sohn also exited and founded the [[New Conservative Party (South Korea)|New Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 19 January 2020|title= \uc0c8\ubcf4\uc218\ub2f9 \ucc3d\ub2f9 \u201c\ucd1d\uc120\uc11c 80\uc11d \ubaa9\ud45c\u201d\u2026\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9 \u201c\ubcf4\uc218\ud1b5\ud569 \ub3d9\ucc38\uc744\u201d|url= http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/politics/assembly/923241.html|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> As a \"conservative union\", the Liberty Korea Party, Onward for Future 4.0, and the New Conservative Party agreed to merge and establish a new party.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 13 February 2020|title= \ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9, \uc0c8\ubcf4\uc218\u00b7\uc804\uc9c4\ub2f9\uacfc \ud569\ub2f9\u2026\uc2e0\ub2f9\uba85 \u2018\ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9\u2019|url= http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200213/99678721/2|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe new party's name was initially set as the '''Grand Unified New Party''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \ub300\ud1b5\ud569\uc2e0\ub2f9),<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 11 February 2020|title= \ubcf4\uc218 \ud1b5\ud569\uc2e0\ub2f9 \ub2f9\uba85, \u2018\ub300\ud1b5\ud569\uc2e0\ub2f9\u2019 \uc7a0\uc815 \uacb0\uc815|url= http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200211/99629252/1|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> but soon changed to the current name.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 14 February 2020|title= \ubcf4\uc218\ud1b5\ud569\uc2e0\ub2f9 \ub2f9\uba85 '\ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9'\uc73c\ub85c \uacb0\uc815|url= http://monthly.chosun.com/client/mdaily/daily_view.asp?idx=8842&Newsnumb=2020028842|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> [[Park Hyung-joon]], who led the merger and refoundation, explained that the name shows both support for youths and political solidarity.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 13 February 2020|title= '\ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9'\uc73c\ub85c...\uada4\ub3c4 \uc624\ub978 \ud1b5\ud569\uc5f4\ucc28|url= https://www.sedaily.com/NewsVIew/1YYWO8UZ3I|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Founding congress ===\nOn 17 February 2020, 3 conservative parties were finally merged and refounded as the United Future Party.<ref name=\"future\"/> It soon elected Liberty Korea president Hwang Kyo-ahn as the new President.<ref name=\"united\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 17 February 2020|title= \ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \ub300\ud45c\uc5d0 \ud669\uad50\uc548\u2026\ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9 \"\ub3cc\uace0 \ub3cc\uc544 \uc0c8\ub204\ub9ac\ub2f9\"|url= https://news.jtbc.joins.com/html/111/NB11935111.html|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> Though much of the new party leadership resembles that of the LKP, Vice-Presidents [[Won Hee-ryong]] and [[Kim Y\u014fng-hwan]] are not from the LKP.<ref name=\"united\"/>\n\nThe President of the Republic of Korea Moon Jae-in and the Democratic Party President [[Lee Hae-chan]] congratulated the new party's founding, but it was soon reported that the move was not welcomed by several members.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 17 February 2020|title= `\uc774\ud574\ucc2c\u2192\uc774\ubc18\ucc2c`\u2026\ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \ucc3d\ub2f9\uc2dd\uc11c \uc218\ub09c\uacaa\uc740 \uc5ec\uad8c \ud654\ud658|url= https://www.mk.co.kr/news/politics/view/2020/02/163717/|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> Some sources also reported that the party is planning to file a lawsuit against Moon.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 18 February 2020|title= \ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \u201c\ubb38\uc7ac\uc778 \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \uc120\uac70\uac1c\uc785 \ud610\uc758\ub85c \uace0\ubc1c\u201d|url= http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/politics/assembly/928650.html|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 18 February 2020|title= \ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9, \ubb38\uc7ac\uc778 \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \uace0\ubc1c \uac80\ud1a0\u2026\"\uc120\uac70\ubc95 \uc704\ubc18 \ud610\uc758\"|url= http://www.newsis.com/view/?id=NISX20200218_0000923257|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 18 February 2020|title= \ubb38\uc7ac\uc778 \ub300\ud1b5\ub839 \uace0\ubc1c \uc5f0\uae30\ud55c \ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \u201c\ubbf8\ub8ec \uac83\ubfd0\u2026\uaf2d \ud55c\ub2e4\u201d|url= https://news.joins.com/article/23709149|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Yoo Seong-min]], the former Bareunmirae president, did not attend the founding congress.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 17 February 2020|title= \ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \ucd9c\ubc94\uc2dd \ubd88\ucc38\ud55c \uc720\uc2b9\ubbfc\u2026\uc1c4\uc2e0\ubbf8\ud761 \ubd88\ub9cc?|url= http://news1.kr/articles/?3845066|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref> [[Yoo Young-ha]], a pro-[[Park Geun-hye]] figure, exited the LKP before the formation of the new party.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 18 February 2020|title= \uc720\uc2b9\ubbfc\uc5d0 \ubc18\uac10? \u6734\uce21\uadfc \uc720\uc601\ud558, \ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \ucd9c\ubc94 \ub2f9\uc77c \ud0c8\ub2f9|url= https://news.joins.com/article/23709087|work= |location= |access-date= 18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Since 2020 ===\nThe party contested as an alliance with its sister [[satellite party]], [[Future Korea Party]], in [[2020 South Korean legislative election|2020 election]]. However, some UFP candidates provoked controversies for defamatory remarks, such as [[Cha Myong-jin]] and [[Kim Dae-ho (politician)|Kim Dae-ho]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 9 April 2020|title= \uae40\uc885\uc778, \uae40\ub300\ud638\u00b7\ucc28\uba85\uc9c4 \ub9c9\ub9d0 \ub17c\ub780 \u2018\ub300\uad6d\ubbfc \uc0ac\uacfc\u2019|url= http://www.sisaweek.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=132782|work= |location= |access-date= 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe party suffered a historic defeat in the election since [[1988 South Korean legislative election|1988]], with only gaining 103 over 300 seats (the former was 121/299 at the [[2004 South Korean legislative election|2004 election]]) slightly more than one-third.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 16 April 2020|title= \ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9, \ubcf4\uc218\uc815\ub2f9\u53f2 \ucd5c\uc545\uc758 \ucc38\ud328|url= https://www.nocutnews.co.kr/news/5328793|work= |location= |access-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref> It lost several key-figures i.e. [[Oh Se-hoon]], [[Na Kyung-won]], [[Shim Jae-chul]], [[Kim Jin-tae (politician)|Kim Jin-tae]] and so on.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 16 April 2020|title= \ud669\uad50\uc548\u00b7\uc624\uc138\ud6c8\u00b7\ub098\uacbd\uc6d0 \ub099\uc120\u2026 \ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 '\ub300\uad8c\uc8fc\uc790' \uc0ac\ub77c\uc838|url= http://www.segye.com/newsView/20200416511066?OutUrl=naver|work= |location= |access-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 16 April 2020|title= [2020\uc120\ud0dd] \ub098\uacbd\uc6d0\u00b7\uae40\uc9c4\ud0dc\u00b7\ubbfc\uacbd\uc6b1\u00b7\uc2ec\uc7ac\ucca0.. \uad6d\ubbfc\uc758 \uc2ec\ud310 \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc900 \uc0ac\ub840|url= http://www.newsfreezone.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=228734|work= |location= |access-date= 16 April 2020}}</ref> The party president [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]], who contested for [[Jongno District]], also defeated by the former [[Prime Minister of South Korea|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Nak-yeon]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 15 April 2020|title= [\ub2f9\uc120-\uc11c\uc6b8 \uc885\ub85c] \uc774\ub099\uc5f0, \u201c\uad6d\ub09c \uadf9\ubcf5\uc5d0 \ud63c\uc2e0 \ub178\ub825 \ud560 \uac83\u201d|url= http://cnews.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=202004152325409437d9fbed771_16|work= |location= |access-date= 15 April 2020}}</ref> Hwang announced he would stand down as the party president.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 15 April 2020|title= [\uc18d\ubcf4]\ud669\uad50\uc548 \ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \ub300\ud45c\uc9c1 \uc0ac\ud1f4\u2026 \"\ucd1d\uc120 \uacb0\uacfc \ucc45\uc784\uc9c0\uaca0\ub2e4\"|url= https://biz.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/04/15/2020041502283.html?utm_source=naver&utm_medium=original&utm_campaign=biz|work= |location= |access-date= 15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 15 April 2020|title= [\uc18d\ubcf4] \ubbf8\ub798\ud1b5\ud569\ub2f9 \ud669\uad50\uc548 \u201c\ubaa8\ub4e0 \ub2f9\uc9c1 \ub0b4\ub824\ub193\uaca0\ub2e4\u201d|url= http://news.kbs.co.kr/news/view.do?ncd=4425633&ref=A|work= |location= |access-date= 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\n=== Chairman ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Name !! Photo !! Began !! Left\n|-\n| 1 || [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]] || [[File:Hwang Kyo-ahn December 2016.jpg|90px|center]] || 17 February 2020 || 15 April 2020\n|}\n\n=== Assembly Leader ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Name !! Photo !! Began !! Left\n|-\n| 1 || [[Shim Jae-chul]] || [[File:\uc2ec\uc7ac\ucca0 \uc6d0\ub0b4\ub300\ud45c.jpg|90px|center]] || 17 February 2020 || Incumbent\n|}\n=== Secretary-General ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Name !! Photo !! Began !! Left\n|-\n| 1 || [[Park Wan-soo]] |||| 17 February 2020 || Incumbent\n|}\n\n== Election results ==\n=== General elections ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:100%; line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=\"50px\"| Election\n! colspan=\"3\"| [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=\"170px\"| Government\n! rowspan=\"2\" | President\n|-\n! width=\"85px\"| Votes\n! width=\"50px\"| %\n! width=\"100px\"| Seats won\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|[[2020 South Korean legislative election|2020]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|11,915,277\n| rowspan=\"2\"|41.5%\n| rowspan=\"2\"|{{Composition bar|103|300|hex=#EF426F}} \n| style=\"background-color:#FFCCCC\"| Opposition\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Portal|Conservatism}}\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n<reference